\end{equation}
The corresponding encoding process is shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:two-tone-encode-example}, where four data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_1,\boldsymbol{d}_2,\boldsymbol{d}_3,\boldsymbol{d}_4$ are encoded into three parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_1,\boldsymbol{c}_2,\boldsymbol{c}_3$. 
Here each data chunk is shifted right by one symbol, unshifted, or shifted left by one symbol and the resulting symbols are XORed to generate parity according to Equations~\eqref{equ:shift-xor-encode} and \eqref{equ:two-tone-shift-offset-mat}. 

