\subsection{Intuitive Implementation of \Twotone}

Algorithm \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-encoding} presents the intuitive encoding realization of \twotone, in which the implementation scans each data chunk symbol-by-symbol and substitutes its XORing contribution into corresponding parity chunk symbols addressed by $s_{i,j}$ of Definition (\ref{def:two-tone}).
The practical consequence of this encoding pattern is that different data-chunk symbols will be dispatched to same parity-chunk symbols dispersedly and repeatedly, which causes bad locality and repeated memory access.

\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\small
\caption{\Twotone Encoding}
\label{algo:two-tone-naive-encoding}
\KwIn{Data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_1,\boldsymbol{d}_2,\ldots,\boldsymbol{d}_{k}$, each of length $l$, \twotone offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$.}
% \KwIn{Data-chunk pointers $d$, parity-chunk pointers $c$, the number of data chunks $k$, the number of parity chunks $m$, chunk length $l$, the offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$.}
\KwOut{Parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_1,\boldsymbol{c}_2,\ldots,\boldsymbol{c}_{m}$.}
% \KwOut{Systematic data-chunk pointers $d$ and decoded parity-chunk pointers $c$.}
\For{$j \gets 1$ \KwTo $k$} {
    \For{$x \gets 1$ \KwTo $l$} {
        \For{$i \gets 1$ \KwTo $m$} {
            % $\delta\gets i-1-m/2$\;
            % $s_{i,j} \gets |\delta|\times(\delta>0? ~j-1: ~k-j)$\;
            $c_i[x+s_{i,j}] \gets c_i[x+s_{i,j}] \oplus d_j[x]$\;
        }
    }
}
\end{algorithm} 

Algorithm \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-decoding} describes the \twotone decoding workflow, which has the same three logical phases as Fig. \ref{fig:two-tone-decode-example}: \subs, \ttelim, and repair.  
In the \subs phase, survived data chunks are scanned and substituted into survived parity chunks just like encoding thus sharing the same consequence.
The core \ttelim phase performs iterative recovery of exposed symbols and \subs to other working survived parity chunks; this phase uses a synchronization offset \(\Delta\) to align different shift amounts and ensure that decoded symbols are read and propagated at the correct relative positions.  
Decoding orders are determined by partitioning the surviving parity set around a central index \(j_{\mathrm{mid}}\), which yields two subsystems and enables exposure and recovery to proceed from the ends toward the middle in a deterministic sequence.  
Finally, once all erased data chunks are reconstructed, any erased parity chunk is repaired from the recovered data to restore full redundancy.  
In this intuitive implementation, decoding of erased data chunks is performed separately from the subsequent repair of erased parity chunks, and the traversal pattern is by default centering on data chunks rather than adapting traversal orders to specific erasure cases.

% This operational description emphasizes the buffer-management and offset-alignment responsibilities that a practical \twotone implementation must satisfy to realize correct and ordered decoding.

\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\small
\caption{\Twotone Decoding}
\label{algo:two-tone-naive-decoding}
% \KwIn{Data-chunk pointers $d$, parity-chunk pointers $c$, the number of data chunks $k$, the number of parity chunks $m$, chunk length $l$, ascendingly sorted indices of survived parity chunks $I_{svd}$, indices of erased parity chunks $I_{erd}$, indices of survived data chunks $J_{svd}$, indices of erased data chunks $J_{erd}$, the offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$}
\KwIn{Ascendingly sorted indices of survived parity chunks $I_{svd}$, indices of erased parity chunks $I_{erd}$, indices of survived data chunks $J_{svd}$, indices of erased data chunks $J_{erd}$, survived data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{svd}$, survived parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_i, i\in I_{svd}$, \twotone offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$}
\KwOut{Decoded data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{erd}$, repaired parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_i,i\in I_{erd}$}
