\subsection{\SXOR and \Twotone Codes}

%Unlike RS codes that rely on finite-field multiplications, \sxor codes~\cite{sungZigZagDecodableCodeMDS2013,gongZigzagDecodableCodes2017,fuOverheadFreeInPlaceRecovery2014,fuOverheadFreeInPlaceRecovery2015,fuDecodingRepairSchemes2020,chengSuccessivelySolvableShiftAdd2021,fuTwotoneShiftXORStorage2021} replace these operations with simple noncyclic bit-shifts and XORs, thereby achieving lower computational cost in both encoding and decoding~\cite{gongZigzagDecodableCodes2017}.

In this section, we introduce the \sxor codes, \twotone encoding and \twotone decoding. 
\subsubsection{\SXOR Codes} 
By default, a systematic $(k,k+m)$ code is applied. A message is divided into $k$ chunks, $\boldsymbol{d}_1,\boldsymbol{d}_2,\ldots,\boldsymbol{d}_{k}$, each of $l$ symbols length. The first $k$ coded chunks are identical to the message chunks and are called data chunks. The remaining $m$ chunks, $\boldsymbol{c}_1,\boldsymbol{c}_2,\ldots,\boldsymbol{c}_{m}$, are called parity chunks.
A symbol is usually set as the length of SIMD register (e.g. 256~bits or 32~bytes) in implementation.   

The generator matrix for a systematic \sxor code can be characterized by an offset matrix $S=(s_{i,j})$ ($i\in I, j\in J,I=\{1,2,\ldots,m\}, J=\{1,2,\ldots,k\}$), where each $s_{i,j}$ is an nonnegative integer representing shift offset. Then the $i$-th ($i\in I$) coded chunk $\boldsymbol c_{k+i}$ can be obtained by  
\begin{equation}
\label{equ:shift-xor-encode}
c_{i}[x] = \bigoplus_{j\in J} d_j[x-s_{i,j}], 
\quad
\substack{x=1,2,\ldots,l+\max\limits_{j\in J}s_{i,j}}.
\end{equation}
To ensure correctness under boundary conditions, we define any access beyond the valid index range to return zero, i.e., $d_j[x]=0$ for $x\le0$ or $x>l$. 
Parity chunks are longer than data chunks by a constant number of symbols due to shifting, which introduces constant storage overhead. 
%For notational simplicity, we uniformly denote the chunk length by $l$, and treat any data at excess positions as zero.
The encoding process shows that the shifting operation can be easily implemented by address offsets and hence is cost-free. 

\subsubsection{\Twotone Encoding}
Among \sxor codes, \twotone code~\cite{fuTwotoneShiftXORStorage2021} generalized the previous constructions~\cite{sungZigZagDecodableCodeMDS2013,fuOverheadFreeInPlaceRecovery2014,fuOverheadFreeInPlaceRecovery2015,fuDecodingRepairSchemes2020} and is the SOTA work. 
The offset matrix of \twotone codes is defined as follows.
\begin{definition}[\Twotone Matrix~\cite{fuTwotoneShiftXORStorage2021}]
\label{def:two-tone} 
An $m\times k$ matrix $\mathbf{S}=\left({s_{i,j}}\right)$ is said to be \textit{\twotone} if for certain integer $0\leq d\leq m$ the following conditions hold:
\begin{enumerate}
\item for any $1\leq i_1<i_2\leq m$, $1\leq j_1<j_2\leq k$, $s_{i_1,j_2}-s_{i_1,j_1}<s_{i_2,j_2}-s_{i_2,j_1}$;
\item for any $1\leq i\leq d$, $1\leq j_1<j_2\leq k$, $t_{i,j_2}-t_{i,j_1}\leq 0$;
\item for any $d<i\leq m$, $1\leq j_1<j_2\leq k$, $t_{i,j_2}-t_{i,j_1}>0$.
\end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

