\subsubsection{\Twotone Decoding}

The highly structured \twotone construction allows the \emph{successive decoding}~\cite{chengSuccessivelySolvableShiftAdd2021}, where each decoded bit can be predetermined rather than brute search.

We use the previous example to illustrate the \twotone decoding, assuming that the survived data chunks are $\boldsymbol{d}_3,\boldsymbol{d}_4$ and parity chunks are $\boldsymbol{c}_1,\boldsymbol{c}_3$. The decoding process and repair of $\boldsymbol{c}_2$ are shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:two-tone-decode-example}.

Firstly, the data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_3,\boldsymbol{d}_4$ are substituted and eliminated from $\boldsymbol{c}_1,\boldsymbol{c}_3$. 
Secondly, the \ttelim is executed to decode $\boldsymbol{d}_1,\boldsymbol{d}_2$. More concretely, the first bits of $\boldsymbol{d}_1,\boldsymbol{d}_2$ can be obtained directly. Substitute $d_1[1]$ and $d_2[1]$ into $\boldsymbol{c}_3$ and $\boldsymbol{c}_1$ respectively, $d_1[2]$ and $d_2[2]$ are retrieved as $d_1[2]=c_3[2]\oplus d_2[1]$ and $d_2[2]=c_1[4]\oplus d_1[1]$. Similarly, substituting $d_1[2]$ and $d_2[2]$ into $\boldsymbol{c}_3$ and $\boldsymbol{c}_1$ respectively, $d_1[3]$ and $d_2[3]$ are retrieved as $d_1[3]=c_3[3]\oplus d_2[2]$ and $d_2[3]=c_1[5]\oplus d_1[2]$. Finally, all bits $d_1[\ell]$ and $d_2[\ell]$ are decoded sequentially.
After the decoding, the $\boldsymbol{c}_2$ is repaired by re-encoding using the data chunks. As $s_{2,i}=0$ for all $1\leq i\leq 4$, $\boldsymbol{c}_2=\boldsymbol{d}_1+\boldsymbol{d}_2+\boldsymbol{d}_3+\boldsymbol{d}_4$.

%Fig.~\ref{fig:two-tone-decode-example} shows a decoding example for the \twotone code with parameters $k=4$ and $m=3$, where four data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_1,\boldsymbol{d}_2,\boldsymbol{d}_3,\boldsymbol{d}_4$ are protected by three parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_1,\boldsymbol{c}_2,\boldsymbol{c}_3$.  The figure focuses on the decoding process: surviving data chunks (in this instance $\boldsymbol{d}_3,\boldsymbol{d}_4$) are fist substituted into the survived parity buffers according to the windowed zero shift offsets so that the contributions of available data are absorbed and symbols associated with erased chunks become exposed; exposed symbols are iteratively decoded from the outermost parity equations and eliminated from the remaining survived parity chunks in a two-sided fashion, with the process proceeding from the ends toward the middle as determined by the offset layout; finally, once all erased data symbols are recovered, any erased parity chunk (here $\boldsymbol{c}_2$) is re-encoded from the recovered data to restore full redundancy. The illustration emphasizes that the windowed zero Shift Offset Matrix (Equation~\ref{equ:two-tone-shift-offset-mat}) prescribes the \subs and elimination order, enabling sequential solvability and avoiding exhaustive offset scans, which yields higher decoding efficiency compared with a generic shift–XOR construction.

