\subsection{Intuitive Implementation of \Twotone}

Algorithm \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-encoding} presents the intuitive encoding realization of \twotone, in which the implementation scans each data chunk symbol-by-symbol and substitutes its XORing contribution into corresponding parity chunk symbols addressed by $s_{i,j}$ of Definition (\ref{def:two-tone}).
The practical consequence of this encoding pattern is that different data-chunk symbols will be dispatched to same parity-chunk symbols dispersedly and repeatedly, which causes bad locality and repeated memory access.

\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\small
\caption{\Twotone Encoding}
\label{algo:two-tone-naive-encoding}
\KwIn{Data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_1,\boldsymbol{d}_2,\ldots,\boldsymbol{d}_{k}$, each of length $l$, \twotone offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$.}
% \KwIn{Data-chunk pointers $d$, parity-chunk pointers $c$, the number of data chunks $k$, the number of parity chunks $m$, chunk length $l$, the offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$.}
\KwOut{Parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_1,\boldsymbol{c}_2,\ldots,\boldsymbol{c}_{m}$.}
% \KwOut{Systematic data-chunk pointers $d$ and decoded parity-chunk pointers $c$.}
\For{$j \gets 1$ \KwTo $k$} {
    \For{$x \gets 1$ \KwTo $l$} {
        \For{$i \gets 1$ \KwTo $m$} {
            % $\delta\gets i-1-m/2$\;
            % $s_{i,j} \gets |\delta|\times(\delta>0? ~j-1: ~k-j)$\;
            $c_i[x+s_{i,j}] \gets c_i[x+s_{i,j}] \oplus d_j[x]$\;
        }
    }
}
\end{algorithm} 

Algorithm \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-decoding} describes the \twotone decoding workflow, which has the same three logical phases as Fig. \ref{fig:two-tone-decode-example}: \subs, \ttelim, and repair.  
In the \subs phase, survived data chunks are scanned and substituted into survived parity chunks just like encoding thus sharing the same consequence.
The core \ttelim phase performs iterative recovery of exposed symbols and \subs to other working survived parity chunks; this phase uses a synchronization offset \(\Delta\) to align different shift amounts and ensure that decoded symbols are read and propagated at the correct relative positions.  
Decoding orders are determined by partitioning the surviving parity set around a central index \(j_{\mathrm{mid}}\), which yields two subsystems and enables exposure and recovery to proceed from the ends toward the middle in a deterministic sequence.  
Finally, once all erased data chunks are reconstructed, any erased parity chunk is repaired from the recovered data to restore full redundancy.  
In this intuitive implementation, decoding of erased data chunks is performed separately from the subsequent repair of erased parity chunks, and the traversal pattern is by default centering on data chunks rather than adapting traversal orders to specific erasure cases.

% This operational description emphasizes the buffer-management and offset-alignment responsibilities that a practical \twotone implementation must satisfy to realize correct and ordered decoding.

\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\small
\caption{\Twotone Decoding}
\label{algo:two-tone-naive-decoding}
% \KwIn{Data-chunk pointers $d$, parity-chunk pointers $c$, the number of data chunks $k$, the number of parity chunks $m$, chunk length $l$, ascendingly sorted indices of survived parity chunks $I_{svd}$, indices of erased parity chunks $I_{erd}$, indices of survived data chunks $J_{svd}$, indices of erased data chunks $J_{erd}$, the offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$}
\KwIn{Ascendingly sorted indices of survived parity chunks $I_{svd}$, indices of erased parity chunks $I_{erd}$, indices of survived data chunks $J_{svd}$, indices of erased data chunks $J_{erd}$, survived data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{svd}$, survived parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_i, i\in I_{svd}$, \twotone offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$}
\KwOut{Decoded data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{erd}$, repaired parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_i,i\in I_{erd}$}
% $c^{cpd}\gets allocate(m\times l)$; $memcpy(c \rightarrow c^{cpd}, m\times l)$\;
% \tcc{Line1-7:$Substitution(d[J_{svd}] \rightarrow c^{cpd}[I_{svd}])$}
\tcc{Line1-7:$Substitution(d[J_{svd}] \rightarrow c[I_{svd}])$}
\ForEach{$j \in J_{svd}$} {
    \For{$x \gets 1$ \KwTo $l$} {
        \ForEach{$i \in I_{svd}$} {
            % $\delta\gets i-1-m/2$\;
            % $s_{i,j} \gets |\delta|\times(\delta<0?~j-1:~k-j)$\;
            % $c^{cpd}_i[x+s_{i,j}] \gets c^{cpd}_i[x+s_{i,j}] \oplus d_j[x]$\;
            $c_i[x+s_{i,j}] \gets c_i[x+s_{i,j}] \oplus d_j[x]$\;
        }
    }
}
% \tcc{Line8-17:$Elimination(d[J_{erd}]\leftrightarrow c^{cpd}[I_{svd}]])$}
\tcc{Line8-17:$Elimination(d[J_{erd}]\leftrightarrow c[I_{svd}]])$}
$j_{mid}\gets\mathop{argmin}\limits_j|I_{svd}[j]-1-m/2|$\;
\For{$x \gets min(2-m/2,1)$ \KwTo $l$} {
    \For{\textnormal{(}$j_{idx} \gets |J_{erd}|$ \KwTo $j_{mid}+1$\textnormal{)}  \\ \quad~~\textnormal{\textbf{then}} \textnormal{(}$j_{idx} \gets 1$ \KwTo $j_{mid}$\textnormal{)}} {
        $j \gets J_{erd}[j_{idx}]$; $i \gets I_{svd}[j_{idx}]$\;
        % $\delta\gets i-1-m/2$; $\Delta\gets max(|\delta| - 1, 0)$\;
        % $s_{i,j} \gets |\delta|\times(\delta<0? ~j-1: ~k-j)$\;
        $\Delta\gets max(|i-1-m/2| - 1, 0)$\;
        $d_j[x+\Delta]\gets c_i[x+\Delta+s_{i,j}]$\;
        $Substitute(d_j[x+\Delta] \rightarrow c[I_{svd}-i])$\;
    }
}
% Repair $c[I_{erd}]$; $free(c^{cpd})$\;
Repair $c[I_{erd}]$\;
\end{algorithm} 



\subsection{Motivation}\label{subsec:motiv}

% Motivation:
% 1.For both the encoding and decoding processes, directly implementing the \sxor calculation of the original algorithm can lead to low computational intensity as well as poor temporal and spatial data locality, which makes the program highly memory-bound.
% 2.For the encoding process, (need a point for Neighbor-merging Access)
% 3.For the decoding process, the shifting pattern of \twotone can produce asymmetric decoding computational routes, depending on whether the data or parity chunks are erasured. On the one hand, we observe that some memory accesses are trivial and can be reduced by process optimization. On the other hand, using the same chunk traversal strategy to uniformly tackle different cases of data/parity chunk losses can lead to suboptimal performance.
% Methodology:
% 1.Cache-friendly Window Partitioning → Motivation 1)
% 2.Neighbor-merging Access → Motivation 2)
% 3.Erasure–Parity Mapping → Motivation 3)
% 4.Traversal Pattern Selection → Motivation 3)

Although \twotone \sxor codes are theoretically simple and efficient, a direct implementation based on Algorithms \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-encoding} and \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-decoding} leads to significant performance degradation and fails to exploit the full potential of the \twotone approach.
Although prior studies \cite{zhouFastErasureCoding2020,wangFastAccelerationStrategies2025} have proposed acceleration techniques for Reed-Solomon (RS) codes, these methods cannot be directly applied to \twotone \sxor due to fundamentally different computational patterns. Specifically, we identify the key performance challenges and optimization opportunities as follows.

% \paragraph{\textbf{Redundant Memory Access and Poor Temporal Locality}} As illustrated in Fig. \ref{fig:two-tone-example}, the original encoding process scans data chunks sequentially, requiring full access to every parity chunk for each update. 
\paragraph{\textbf{Redundant Memory Access and Poor Temporal Locality}} As illustrated in Algorithm \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-encoding}, the original encoding process scans data chunks sequentially, requiring full access to every parity chunk for each update. 
This leads to redundant memory accesses and poor temporal locality when modifying parity data. Similarly, the decoding process suffers from analogous issues during the \subs and \ttelim phases. These inefficiencies render the implementation memory-bound.

\paragraph{\textbf{Inefficient Data Traversal Pattern of Encoding}} It is natural to raise two traversal patterns for data chunks in \twotone \sxor encoding: horizontal and vertical. Horizontal traversal (adopted by the intuitive implementation as shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:TwoToneEncodePatterns}(a)) minimizes redundant data reads but incurs multiple redundant parity writes, while vertical traversal reduces parity writes at the cost of repeatedly loading the same data chunks. Both approaches suffer from significant memory inefficiencies, either in parity traffic or data locality, that degrade performance on memory-bound architectures. 


\paragraph{\textbf{Complex Decoding Process with Suboptimal Traversal Pattern}} Most existing studies prioritize timely repair solutions for data chunks while adopting lazy approaches for parity chunks. However, in our implementation, we assert that parity chunks are equally critical as data chunks, as failure to restore parity chunks promptly can result in catastrophic data unavailability. Guided by this principle, we observe that jointly repairing both data and parity chunks, rather than treating them separately, can improve performance by eliminating redundant operations. Additionally, employing a uniform chunk traversal pattern across all cases of data/parity chunk losses leads to suboptimal performance.
%, as it fails to account for case-specific optimizations.

We conclude that the aforementioned performance limitations stem from inefficient memory access patterns. Specifically, the unnecessary repeated operations and suboptimal data traversal patterns can collectively degrade computational intensity and spatial/temporal locality. To address these memory-bound challenges, we propose a systematic set of optimization techniques, integrated into a novel \twotone implementation called \design. \design focuses on: 1) reducing redundant memory operations to enhance memory access efficiency; 2) optimizing data traversal patterns to improve temporal locality.
Using this cohesive optimization framework, \design bridges the gap between the theoretical efficiency of \twotone and its practical high-performance implementation, ensuring robust and scalable storage system performance.

%\paragraph{Memory Access Optimization} 
%As line 2 and 6 in Algorithm \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-encoding} \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-decoding} demonstrates, the whole parity-chunk symbols are updated from the very begining to the end for $k$ times, resulting in bad cache locality and many repeated memory access. 

%\paragraph{Special Case Optimization}
%Since chunk-level XOR is the basic operation, cases with only one chunk erased could be easily solved by XORing all corresponding chunks without windowed zero eliminating. And such cases representing only one node down in the distributed system are actually common where the failed one will be repaired(decoded) immediately to avoid more failures.

%First, most existing implementations are tailored to specific erasure patterns and cannot seamlessly handle arbitrary combinations of data and parity losses. This lack of generality limits their applicability in production environments, where both data recovery and parity regeneration are essential. Second, naïve implementations often suffer from poor cache locality and excessive memory traffic due to scattered access patterns and unnecessary buffer initialization, creating a memory bottleneck that constrains throughput. Third, common scenarios such as single-chunk erasures are not fully optimized to exploit hardware capabilities such as SIMD instructions, leaving potential performance gains untapped.


%Survived parity chunks are copied. Parity-chunk re-encoding could be integrated into data-chunk decoding because of the same type of calculating.

%Addressing these challenges requires a holistic approach that combines algorithmic generalization with system-level performance engineering. In this work, we integrate a generalized windowed zero Shift–XOR codec into the Ceph distributed storage platform as a production-ready erasure coding plugin. This integration enables standardized functional testing and fair performance comparisons against state-of-the-art codecs, including Intel ISA-L for RS codes, Jerasure, and ZigZag for shift–XOR codes. Within this framework, we design and evaluate a set of optimizations—such as unified erasure–parity mapping, cache-friendly windowing, and neighbor-merging memory access—that are specifically tailored to shift–XOR codes. Our goal is to establish a high-performance implementation methodology that not only surpasses existing Ceph plugins and recent research prototypes in throughput, but also advances the practical adoption of shift–XOR erasure codes in large-scale distributed storage systems.

%We also exploit hardware capabilities such as SIMD instructions.

%By bridging the gap between theoretical algorithm design and engineering practice, this work contributes both a concrete performance improvement and a reusable optimization framework. The resulting methodology enhances the decoding and encoding throughput of erasure codes, aligns the performance of coding operations with that of modern high-speed storage and networking hardware~\cite{weiCharacterizingOptimizingRemote2021}, and enriches the set of coding options available to the open-source storage community.

