\begin{figure}[hpbt]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.94\linewidth]{figs/Two-tone Optimization Overview.pdf}
    \caption{The Workload Overview of \design.}
    \label{fig:opt-overview}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Cache-Friendly Window Partitioning}

As discussed in Section \ref{subsec:motiv}, while sequential data chunk scanning preserves strong spatial locality for data access, this approach incurs repeated traversals of parity chunks during \sxor updates. To resolve this inefficiency, we split every chunk into consecutive, fixed-length \emph{windows} and execute all \sxor operations within a single window before progressing to the next, as illustrated in Fig. \ref{fig:CacheFriendlyWindow}.
\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.94\linewidth]{figs/Cache-Friendly Window Demonstration.pdf}
  \caption{Demonstration of Cache-Friendly Window Partitioning. Colored segments indicate local access within the same window. Shaded regions in the parity chunk represent overlaps with adjacent windows.}
  \label{fig:CacheFriendlyWindow}
\end{figure}

% Writing
% Decoding consists of two sequential phases, \subs followed by \ttelim, each accessing the window sequence with a fixed offset. We advance \subs by one window relative to \ttelim. As illustrated in Fig. \ref{fig:CacheFriendlyWindow}, naively aligned \subs populates only the first window of $\boldsymbol d_1$ and $\boldsymbol d_2$, leaving the first windows of $\boldsymbol d_3$ and $\boldsymbol d_4$ partly untouched. By advancing \subs one window ahead, the \subs of $\boldsymbol d_1$ and $\boldsymbol d_2$ covers all first-window positions that \ttelim will later read, ensuring correctness while preserving small-window locality.

Both encoding and decoding operate on demand within cache-sized windows rather than touching entire chunks up front.  
%Parity-chunk windows (in encoding) and erased-chunk windows (in decoding) should be treated as undefined memory in general erasure coding storage.
Rather than initializing the entire chunks at start, we initialize them lazily by initializing a window on its first use.
%which confines zero-initialization traffic to the small subset of windows actually accessed. 
Under windowed encoding, the standard \sxor updates are applied inside each window so that parity contributions from nearby symbols remain temporally and spatially local, reducing repeated long-range parity accesses and improving cache reuse when updating parity chunks.  

Windowed decoding applies the similar route. \Subs and \ttelim are executed over the same small working-window sequence, which restricts reads and writes to a compact address range and improves cache locality.  
To ensure that \ttelim never consumes an undefined location, \subs is advanced by one window relative to \ttelim so that earlier \subs work always populates the positions that \ttelim will subsequently read; 
meeting this coverage requirement implies a lower bound on the window size, namely the window must span at least \(k-1\) symbol positions to cover all relative offsets introduced by the \twotone offset matrix when substitution is advanced by one window.  
Consequently, we select the minimal power-of-two window size \(W\) satisfying \(W\ge k-1\) to combine alignment simplicity with the required coverage, and our experiments show that this smallest admissible \(W\) provides the best throughput trade-off in practice.



\subsection{Neighbor-Merging Access}

\begin{figure*}[t!]
    \centering
    \begin{minipage}[t]{0.27\textwidth}
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.6\linewidth]{figs/Two-tone Horizontal Access Pattern.pdf}\\
        \textbf{(a) Horizontal traversal}
    \end{minipage}
    \hfill
    \begin{minipage}[t]{0.6\textwidth}
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.75\linewidth]{figs/Two-tone Vertical Access Pattern.pdf}\\
        \textbf{(b) Vertical traversal}
    \end{minipage}
    \caption{Basic \Twotone Traversal Patterns: (a) per-data-chunk-symbol traversal yields strong data locality but fragmented parity writes; (b) per-parity-chunk-symbol traversal concentrates parity updates but repeats data reads.}
    \label{fig:TwoToneEncodePatterns}
\end{figure*}

Intuitively, there are two chunk traversal patterns in Two‐tone Shift‐XOR encoding: horizontal and vertical patterns. 
In the horizontal traversal (Fig.~\ref{fig:TwoToneEncodePatterns}(a)), the encoder reads each data‐chunk symbol in sequence and immediately applies XOR updates across all corresponding parity‐chunk symbols. 
In the figure, dashed arrows indicate the direction of memory operations, and the numbers on these arrows denote the chronological order of the accesses. 
This pattern ensures that every data symbol is consumed exactly once, but each parity symbol is updated multiple times, inflating overall parity‐access traffic. 
The total complexity of memory access for this pattern is approximately $\Theta((k+km)l)$, where $k$ is the number of data chunks, $m$ the number of parity chunks and $l$ the length of the chunk in symbols.

In the vertical traversal (Fig.~\ref{fig:TwoToneEncodePatterns}(b)), the loop centers on parity‐chunk symbols: for each parity‐chunk symbol, the encoder gathers all corresponding data‐chunk symbols, computes their XOR in one pass, and writes the final parity‐chunk symbol exactly once. 
This avoids redundant parity‐chunk access, but each data‐chunk symbol is reloaded for each parity‐chunk chunk, leading to a memory‐access complexity of roughly $\Theta((m+km)l)$. 
Although $k$ is typically larger than $m$, the difference in total access count between the two patterns is not dramatic, because vertical traversal must jump between $k$ independent data‐chunk memory regions at a symbol granularity, which slightly worsens locality compared to horizontal traversal.

To reduce both writing and reading operations, we propose a neighbor‐merging access pattern. 
During a horizontal pass, adjacent fixed length data-chunk symbols are loaded into SIMD registers, each register exactly holding one symbol, and merged via a single in‐register XOR. The merged result is then XORed into the corresponding parity-chunk symbol. In Fig. \ref{fig:NeighborMergingAccessPattern}, a right brace highlights that the two data contributions are first XOR‐merged in registers before any parity‐chunk update. This approach yields a memory‐access complexity of about $\Theta(\!\left(k+\frac{km}{2}\right)L)$, which is clearly lower than the horizontal pattern, and will also be lower than the vertical pattern whenever $m(k+2) > 2k$, a condition easily satisfied in practical $(k,m)$ configurations. More importantly, neighbor merging access avoids repeatedly visiting the same data‐chunk memory and reduces the number of accesses to parity‐chunk memory. By performing two‐chunk XORs at the SIMD instruction level, the method further improves the utilization of SIMD lane throughput. We deliberately limit merging to pairs of symbols, as SIMD’s finite register files and the increased offset complexity for more parity chunks make multi‐chunk merging impractical.


\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figs/Neighbor-Merging Access Pattern.pdf}
  \caption{Demonstration of the Neighbor-Merging Access Pattern. Adjacent data-chunk windows are merged in SIMD registers via XOR and then written back to each parity window in a single contiguous store, reducing write amplification and preserving cache locality.}
  \label{fig:NeighborMergingAccessPattern}
\end{figure}


\subsection{Erasure–Parity Mapping}
\label{subsec:ep-mapping}

In general erasure coding storage, the decoding procedure must guarantee timely recovery of both data chunks and parity chunks. Simply restoring data chunks while neglecting parity chunks compromises the system's redundancy guarantees. That is, if all the parity chunks are erasured and not recovered promptly, a single additional data chunk failure under this condition could render the system unrecoverable, leading to permanent data loss.

A direct implementation of the original \twotone decoding under these constraints leads to the \emph{intuitive} procedure illustrated in Algorithm \ref{algo:two-tone-naive-decoding}. 
In this approach, the decoder must first recover erased data chunks by \emph{\subs} and \emph{\ttelim}, and finally perform a dedicated \emph{Repair} step for re-encoding erased parity chunks. Although correct, this intuitive method introduces redundant operations and additional memory traffic because of separately repairing.

Algorithm~\ref{algo:TwoToneDecodeMapping} presents the decoding procedure based on the proposed \emph{Erasure–Parity Mapping} abstraction. 
The process consists of three steps: (1) \emph{Erasure–Parity Mapping}, (2) \emph{\Subs}, and (3) \emph{\TTElim}. 
In the first step, all erased data and parity chunks are uniformly represented by the structure \texttt{mpe}, which records each erased chunk and the matched survived parity chunk. 
If the erased chunk is itself a parity chunk, it is mapped to its own. 
This unified representation eliminates the need for performing a dedicated repair stage at the end. 
In the second step, all survived data chunks are directly substituted into every \texttt{mpe} entry, following the same Shift–XOR rule. 
Finally, in the \ttelim step, decoding iteratively exposes decoded symbols and immediately substitutes them back into all relevant \texttt{mpe} structures, including those corresponding to erased parity chunks. 
This design reduces redundant memory accesses and avoids repeated traversals, while preserving the theoretical optimality of \twotone decoding.

\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\small
\caption{Erasure–Parity Mapping Decoding}
\label{algo:TwoToneDecodeMapping}
% \KwIn{Data chunks $\boldsymbol d$, parity chunks $\boldsymbol c$, the number of data chunks $k$, the number of parity chunks $m$, chunk length $l$, ascendingly sorted indices of survived parity chunks $I_{svd}$, indices of erased parity chunks $I_{erd}$, indices of survived data chunks $J_{svd}$, indices of erased data chunks $J_{erd}$}
% \KwOut{Decoded data chunks and re-encoded parity chunks}
\KwIn{Ascendingly sorted indices of survived parity chunks $I_{svd}$, indices of erased parity chunks $I_{erd}$, indices of survived data chunks $J_{svd}$, indices of erased data chunks $J_{erd}$, survived data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{svd}$, survived parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_i, i\in I_{svd}$, \twotone offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$}
% \KwOut{Decoded data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{erd}$, repaired parity chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{erd}$}
\KwOut{Decoded data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{erd}$, repaired parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_i,i\in I_{erd}$}
\tcc{Line1-10: $MapErasure(J_{erd}|I_{erd}\leftrightarrow I_{svd})$}
$mpe \gets allocate(m,nullptr)$; $I_{mpd}\gets vector()$\;
\ForEach{$j \in J_{erd}$}{
    $i \gets I_{svd}.pop\_front()$; $I_{mpd}.push\_back(i)$\;
    $mpe[i] \gets \boldsymbol d_j$; \tcp{$d_j[x]$ is undefined}
    $memcpy(\boldsymbol c_i \rightarrow mpe[i], m \times l)$\;
}
\ForEach{$i \in I_{erd}$}{
    $mpe[i] \gets \boldsymbol c_i$; \tcp{$c_i[x]$ is undefined}
    $memset(0 \rightarrow mpe[i], m \times l)$\;
}
$Substitution(\boldsymbol d[J_{svd}] \rightarrow mpe[I_{mpd}+I_{erd}])$\;
$Elimination(mpe[I_{mpd}] \leftrightarrow mpe[I_{mpd}+I_{erd}])$\;
\end{algorithm}

Figure~\ref{fig:erasuer-parity-mapping-decoding} illustrates an example of this decoding process. 
Suppose $\boldsymbol d_1$, $\boldsymbol d_2$, and $\boldsymbol c_2$ are erased. 
The mapping step constructs three associations: $\boldsymbol d_1 \leftrightarrow \boldsymbol c_3$, $\boldsymbol c_2 \leftrightarrow \boldsymbol c_2$ (self-mapping), and $\boldsymbol d_2 \leftrightarrow \boldsymbol c_1$. 
Then survived data chunks $\boldsymbol d_3$, and $\boldsymbol d_4$ are substituted into these mappings. 
During \ttelim, exposed symbols are orderly propagated into other mappings. 
In the figure, dashed arrows and strikethrough annotations indicate operations that are no longer required.
And the repair of erased parity chunks is now integrated into the \ttelim step. 
This unified process reduces redundant memory access.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figs/Erasure-Parity Mapping Decoding Demonstration.pdf}
  \caption{Erasure–Parity Mapping Decoding Example. Dashed arrows and strikethrough annotations indicate eliminated operations.}
  \label{fig:erasuer-parity-mapping-decoding}
\end{figure}

By consolidating erased data and parity chunks into a single abstraction, the Erasure–Parity Mapping technique minimizes memory traffic and traversal cost, while maintaining the optimal decoding properties of the \twotone algorithm. 
For the special case where only one single chunk (either data or parity) is erased, this whole framework is technically applicable but unnecessary; a dedicated lightweight optimization will be introduced in the next subsection.

\subsection{Traversal Pattern Selection}

In large-scale storage clusters, failure patterns are strongly biased toward single-erasure events. The probability of losing two or more chunks simultaneously is obviously lower than that of losing exactly one chunk. 
This observation motivates a dedicated optimization for the case that a single data chunk or a single parity chunk is missing.  

For this scenario, the decoder does not need to execute the full \ttelim procedure, which normally involves iteratively constructing and solving multiple erasure equations. Instead, recovery can be completed by performing a single global XOR over all necessary surviving chunks, directly producing the missing chunk in one pass. Since the operation touches each relevant chunk symbol exactly once, it is well suited to the vertical traversal patterns described in Fig.~\ref{fig:TwoToneEncodePatterns}(b), which in this case achieves higher access efficiency than the horizontal pattern because no repeated access occurs. 

Algorithm~\ref{algo:traversal-pattern-selection} presents the generalized decoding procedure with \emph{Traversal Pattern Selection}, which complements the unified framework introduced earlier. The decoder first performs \emph{Erasure–Parity Mapping} to construct the mapping structure, and then selects between two traversal patterns based on the number of erasures. When exactly one chunk (either data or parity) is erased, the decoder bypasses the full \ttelim and performs a single pass of vertical traversal that XORs all necessary survived chunks to directly reconstruct the missing chunk. Otherwise, it falls back to the standard path of \emph{\subs} followed by \emph{\ttelim}.

\begin{algorithm}
\small
\caption{Traversal Pattern Selection Decoding}
\label{algo:traversal-pattern-selection}
% \KwIn{Data chunks $\boldsymbol d$, parity chunks $\boldsymbol c$, the number of data chunks $k$, the number of parity chunks $m$, chunk length $l$, ascendingly sorted indices of survived parity chunks $I_{svd}$, indices of erased parity chunks $I_{erd}$, indices of survived data chunks $J_{svd}$, indices of erased data chunks $J_{erd}$}
% \KwOut{Decoded data chunks and re-encoded parity chunks}
\KwIn{Ascendingly sorted indices of survived parity chunks $I_{svd}$, indices of erased parity chunks $I_{erd}$, indices of survived data chunks $J_{svd}$, indices of erased data chunks $J_{erd}$, survived data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{svd}$, survived parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_i, i\in I_{svd}$, \twotone offset matrix $(s_{i,j})$}
\KwOut{Decoded data chunks $\boldsymbol{d}_j,j\in J_{erd}$, repaired parity chunks $\boldsymbol{c}_i,i\in I_{erd}$}
$MapErasure(J_{erd}\,|\,I_{erd}\leftrightarrow I_{svd})$\;
\tcc{Traversal Pattern Selection}
\If{$|J_{erd}|+|I_{erd}|==1$} {
    \tcc{Vertical pattern reconstruction (single pass)}
    % $i\gets I_{mpd}[1]$; $\delta\gets i-1-m/2$\;
    $i\gets I_{mpd}[1]$\;
    \For{$x \gets 1$ \KwTo $l$} {
        $sum\gets 0$\;
        \ForEach{$j \in J_{svd}$} {
            % $s_{ij} \gets |\delta| \times (\delta<0~?~j-1~:~k-j)$\;
            $sum\gets sum \oplus d_j[x-s_{ij}]$\;
        }
        $mpe[i][x] \gets sum$;
    }
}
\Else {
    \tcc{Standard unified decoding}
    $Substitution(\boldsymbol d[J_{svd}] \rightarrow mpe[I_{mpd}+I_{erd}])$\;
    $Elimination(mpe[I_{mpd}]~from~mpe[I_{mpd}+I_{erd}])$\;
}
\end{algorithm}

Figure~\ref{fig:SpecialCaseOneErasure} illustrates the single-erasure case and the efficacy of the vertical traversal pattern. When only one chunk is missing (e.g., $\boldsymbol d_2$ or $\boldsymbol c_1$), the decoder performs a single global XOR across all relevant survived chunks to produce the erased chunk in one pass, without \ttelim. This branch introduces negligible overhead and yields a highly memory-efficient recovery path for one-erasure cases.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figs/Vertical Traversal Pattern Demonstration.pdf}
  \caption{Vertical Traversal Pattern Demonstration for Single-Erasure Recovery. The missing chunk is reconstructed via a single pass of XOR over survived chunks, without \ttelim.}
  \label{fig:SpecialCaseOneErasure}
\end{figure}

