\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:futureworks}

While \design proposes four optimization techniques for \twotone \sxor erasure codes and achieves remarkable throughput improvements over existing solutions, several opportunities for further enhancement remain.
First, the current cache-friendly window partitioning mechanism employs a fixed minimal size, which enhances locality in our tests. However, its optimality across diverse environments remains unclear. Future studies could investigate adaptive or heterogeneous window sizing, as well as alternative partitioning strategies. Second, the neighbor-merging access pattern is constrained by 256-bit register limits and excludes certain parity blocks (e.g., the fourth when $m=4$). While decoding-side merging during \subs yields smaller gains due to erasure pattern sensitivity, this suggests potential for more flexible merging heuristics. Third, our traversal pattern selection primarily optimizes single-erasure recovery. However, some multi-erasure patterns could be decomposed into sequential single-erasure steps to reuse the fast path. Exploring such reducible cases, along with refining the above techniques, could further bridge the gap between theoretical and practical performance. Overall, while the proposed techniques in \design significantly advance the engineering impact of shift–XOR codes, further fine-grained optimizations remain a promising direction for future research.

\section{Related Works}
\label{sec:relatedworks}

With the rapid development of distributed storage systems, erasure coding has become a core technique for fault tolerance and data reliability. Among various schemes, the classical Reed–Solomon (RS) code~\cite{reedPolynomialCodesCertain1960} has achieved significant advances in both theoretical foundations and system-level optimizations. Operating over finite fields, RS codes possess the Maximum Distance Separable (MDS) property, ensuring that the original data can be reconstructed from any $k$ out of $n$ encoded chunks. Early optimizations focused on reducing the computational cost of finite-field multiplications, such as transforming finite-field operations into XOR-based computations~\cite{lubyXORBasedErasureResilientCoding1995} and employing Vandermonde or Cauchy matrices to lower the inversion overhead. On the system side, numerous implementation strategies have been proposed to improve throughput, including matrix sparsification, common subexpression elimination, memory and cache access optimizations, and pointer-related overhead reduction. Cerasure~\cite{wangFastAccelerationStrategies2025} provides a comprehensive summary of these strategies and integrates them into a unified framework, achieving state-of-the-art performance for RS codes under certain conditions.

In recent years, a new line of research has emerged around non-cyclic shift–XOR erasure codes, which replace finite-field multiplications with bit-shift and XOR operations. This design enables linear-time encoding and decoding, reduced CPU overhead, and better suitability for vectorized execution. ZigZag Decodable (ZD) Codes~\cite{gongZigzagDecodableCodes2017} demonstrated the feasibility and efficiency of constructing shift matrices based on Vandermonde or Hankel structures, achieving high performance using only shift and XOR operations. Subsequent work extended ZD Codes to various domains, including storage systems~\cite{daiNewZigzagDecodableCode2017,daiBandwidthOverheadFreeData2017}, wireless networks~\cite{daiZigzagDivisionMultipleAccess2019}, and cryptography~\cite{gongZigzagDecodableRampSecret2018,kabiriradEfficientRampSecret2023,chenNewShiftAddSecret2024}. 

Building on these foundations, \twotone \sxor Codes~\cite{fuTwotoneShiftXORStorage2021} were proposed as a more structured and theoretically rigorous variant. They refine earlier concepts such as the Increasing-Difference~\cite{fuOverheadFreeInPlaceRecovery2014,fuOverheadFreeInPlaceRecovery2015}, Refined Increasing-Difference properties~\cite{fuDecodingRepairSchemes2020} and the Successive Solvability framework~\cite{chengSuccessivelySolvableShiftAdd2021}, to define a symmetric decreasing–increasing shift pattern. This structure partitions the decoding process into two sub-systems corresponding to the decreasing and increasing phases, enabling orderly and efficient recovery of data chunks. The formalism of \twotone codes not only improves decoding clarity and performance but also provides a solid theoretical basis for system-level optimizations.

However, despite the maturity of theoretical research on ZD and \twotone codes, system-level optimization for these schemes remains largely unexplored. The optimization strategies developed for RS codes cannot be directly applied to \twotone \sxor codes. This is because, in shift–XOR codes, all data chunks participate in XOR operations for every parity chunk, making RS-style sparsification ineffective. Furthermore, the varying shift offsets across parity chunks eliminate common subexpressions, and the distinct offset computation and data traversal patterns prevent direct reuse of RS-oriented memory, cache, and pointer optimizations. As a result, there is a clear gap in the literature regarding practical, high-performance implementations of \twotone codes in production-grade distributed storage systems. This work addresses that gap by investigating system-level optimization techniques tailored specifically to the structured nature of \twotone \sxor erasure codes.

