\newcommand{\design}{\textit{FastTT}\xspace}
\newcommand{\sxor}{Shift-XOR\xspace}
\newcommand{\twotone}{Two-tone\xspace}

\title{\design: Accelerating \sxor Erasure Coding for Data Storage}
\author{Duo Sun \and Ximing Fu \and Qiang Wang}
\institute{Harbin Institute of Technology (Shenzhen) \\ Pengcheng Laboratory}
\date{IPDPS 2026}

\begin{document}

\part{\design: Accelerating \sxor Erasure Coding for Data Storage}

% =====================================================================
% Title
% =====================================================================
\begin{frame}
  \titlepage
\end{frame}
\note{
Good afternoon everyone. I am Duo Sun, and I will be presenting our work, FastTT: Accelerating Shift-XOR Erasure Coding for Data Storage. This is joint work with my advisors Ximing Fu and Qiang Wang at HIT Shenzhen and Pengcheng Laboratory. Shift-XOR codes are a family of erasure codes that replace expensive finite-field multiplications with bit-shifts and XORs, and Two-tone is the state-of-the-art construction in this family. The goal of this talk is to show how we turn this theoretically efficient code family into a practical, high-throughput implementation for modern storage systems such as Ceph.
}

% =====================================================================
% Motivation
% =====================================================================
\section{Motivation}
\subsection{Why This Problem Matters}

\begin{frame}[t]{Motivation}
\small
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.54\textwidth}
  \begin{itemize}
    \setlength{\itemsep}{0.6em}
    \item Erasure coding $=$ reliability + low storage cost.
    \item RS dominates production; already heavily optimized.
    \item \twotone \sxor: shifts \& XORs, \textbf{no GF multiplications}.
    \item But direct implementation is \textbf{memory-bound}.
    \item RS-style tricks do \textbf{not} transfer.
  \end{itemize}

  \vspace{0.8em}
  \begin{block}{Our Goal}
  First high-performance, memory-aware implementation of \twotone, validated in Ceph.
  \end{block}

  \column{0.44\textwidth}
  \centering
  \begin{block}{At a glance}
  \centering
  \large
  $k$ data $+$ $m$ parity \\[0.3em]
  parity $=$ shift-XOR of data \\[0.3em]
  \textit{vs.}~RS: no finite-field math
  \end{block}

  \vspace{0.6em}
  {\footnotesize \textbf{Headline:} up to \textbf{182\%} faster decoding \\ vs. state-of-the-art libraries.}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
\note{
Distributed storage must stay reliable under failures, and erasure coding delivers the same reliability as replication at much lower storage cost. Reed-Solomon is the dominant production choice and already benefits from years of system-level optimization, so we are not trying to replace RS. Our focus is Shift-XOR coding, in particular Two-tone, which is the state-of-the-art Shift-XOR construction. The appeal is theoretical: encoding and decoding use only bit-shifts and XORs instead of finite-field multiplications. The gap is practical: a direct Two-tone implementation is memory-bound, and RS-specific tricks like matrix sparsification or common subexpression elimination do not transfer, because the computation and memory-access patterns are fundamentally different. So the goal of this talk is the first high-performance, memory-access-aware implementation of Two-tone, which we call FastTT, validated inside Ceph.
}

% =====================================================================
% Background: Two-tone at a glance
% =====================================================================
\subsection{Two-tone at a Glance}

\begin{frame}[t]{\twotone \sxor in One Slide}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.5\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.58\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Example_of_Two-tone_Encoding.pdf}

  \vspace{0.3em}
  {\scriptsize \textbf{Encoding:} each parity = XOR of shifted data chunks.}

  \column{0.5\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.58\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Example_of_Two-tone_Decoding.pdf}

  \vspace{0.3em}
  {\scriptsize \textbf{Decoding:} substitution $\to$ \twotone elimination $\to$ repair.}
\end{columns}

\vspace{0.4em}
\centering
\begin{minipage}{0.85\linewidth}
\centering
\footnotesize
Structured offset matrix $\Rightarrow$ \emph{successive solvability}: decoding order is predetermined, not searched.
\end{minipage}
\end{frame}
\note{
Before I talk about the bottlenecks, here is Two-tone in one slide. In encoding, the message is split into k data chunks and we produce m parity chunks. Each parity chunk is just the XOR of data chunks that are bit-shifted by amounts given by a structured offset matrix. There are no finite-field multiplications anywhere. In decoding, the workflow has three phases: substitute survived data into survived parity chunks, run a structured "two-tone elimination" to recover erased data symbols in a predetermined order, and finally repair erased parity by re-encoding. The key property that makes Two-tone attractive is successive solvability: because of the special shape of the offset matrix, the decoding order is known in advance, with no brute-force search. Now let us look at why a direct implementation of this does not perform well.
}

% =====================================================================
% Limitations of existing solutions
% =====================================================================
\section{Limitations of Existing Solutions}
\subsection{Encoding: Memory Access \& Traversal Trade-off}

\begin{frame}[t]{Limitations (1/2): Traversal Trade-off in Encoding}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.42\textwidth}
  \begin{itemize}
    \setlength{\itemsep}{0.5em}
    \item Each parity chunk touched \textbf{many times} $\Rightarrow$ poor temporal locality.
    \item \textbf{Horizontal:} good data reads, \textbf{many parity writes}. \;$\Theta((k{+}km)l)$
    \item \textbf{Vertical:} one parity write, \textbf{repeated data reloads}. \;$\Theta((m{+}km)l)$
    \item Neither pattern is memory-efficient.
  \end{itemize}

  \vspace{0.5em}
  \begin{block}{Bottleneck}
  \small Memory-access pattern, \emph{not} the coding arithmetic.
  \end{block}

  \column{0.58\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth,height=0.3\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Two-tone_Horizontal_Access_Pattern.pdf}

  {\tiny (a) Horizontal traversal: per-data-symbol, writes scatter across parity.}

  \vspace{0.4em}

  \includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth,height=0.3\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Two-tone_Vertical_Access_Pattern.pdf}

  {\tiny (b) Vertical traversal: per-parity-symbol, re-reads data chunks.}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
\note{
The first limitation is in the encoding side. Naive Two-tone scans data sequentially and updates parity for every shift, so each parity chunk is touched many times with poor temporal locality. More fundamentally, there are only two natural traversal patterns, and both are memory-inefficient. Horizontal traversal, shown on the top right, iterates data-chunk-by-data-chunk and gives very good spatial locality on data reads, but each parity symbol is written many times, with total memory traffic on the order of k plus k times m times l. Vertical traversal, shown on the bottom right, writes each parity symbol only once, but it constantly reloads data across k independent data chunks, with memory traffic on the order of m plus k times m times l. The practical conclusion is that the bottleneck is memory-access pattern, not the coding arithmetic itself. This shapes the design of FastTT on the encoding side.
}

\subsection{Decoding: Complexity \& Uniform Traversal}

\begin{frame}[t]{Limitations (2/2): Complex Decoding Flow}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.42\textwidth}
  \begin{itemize}
    \setlength{\itemsep}{0.5em}
    \item Naive decoding $=$ recover data, \emph{then} re-encode erased parity in a separate stage.
    \item Redundant passes over overlapping memory regions.
    \item One-size-fits-all traversal ignores the common \textbf{single-erasure} case.
  \end{itemize}

  \vspace{0.5em}
  \begin{block}{Opportunities}
  \small
  Fuse data recovery \& parity repair. \\
  Specialize for the dominant failure case.
  \end{block}

  \column{0.58\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.62\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Two-tone_Naive_Decoding_Flow.pdf}

  \vspace{0.2em}
  {\scriptsize Naive \twotone decoding: data recovery and parity repair are separate stages.}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
\note{
The second limitation is on the decoding side. As shown on the right, naive Two-tone decoding runs data recovery first and then a dedicated parity repair stage. When both data and parity chunks are erased, this split creates redundant passes over overlapping memory regions and extra memory traffic. A second problem is that existing implementations apply exactly the same decoder to every erasure case. In real clusters, the overwhelmingly common case is a single failed chunk, which could be reconstructed by a simple one-pass XOR instead of full elimination. So this slide gives us two clear opportunities: fuse data recovery with parity repair into one unified flow, and specialize the dominant single-erasure case with a fast path. Together with the encoding-side trade-off, these observations motivate the four techniques that make up FastTT.
}

% =====================================================================
% Approach and key ideas
% =====================================================================
\section{Approach and Key Ideas}
\subsection{FastTT Overview}

\begin{frame}[t]{\design Overview}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.42\textwidth}
  \begin{block}{Design principle}
  \small Optimize \twotone by \textbf{memory-access behavior}, not by algorithmic rewriting.
  \end{block}

  \vspace{0.3em}
  \textbf{Four coordinated techniques}
  \begin{enumerate}
    \setlength{\itemsep}{0.25em}
    \item \textbf{CFWP} \,-- Cache-Friendly Window Partitioning
    \item \textbf{NMA} \,-- Neighbor-Merging Access
    \item \textbf{EPM} \,-- Erasure-Parity Mapping
    \item \textbf{TPS} \,-- Traversal Pattern Selection
  \end{enumerate}

  \vspace{0.3em}
  \textit{Encoding:} CFWP $+$ NMA. \\
  \textit{Decoding:} CFWP $+$ EPM $+$ TPS.

  \column{0.58\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.7\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Two-tone_Optimization_Overview.pdf}

  \vspace{0.2em}
  {\scriptsize Overall \design workflow.}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
\note{
This slide sets the story for the rest of the talk. Our design principle is to optimize Two-tone from a system perspective, focusing on memory-access behavior, rather than changing the code construction. FastTT combines four coordinated techniques. Cache-Friendly Window Partitioning reorganizes how the workload flows through memory. Neighbor-Merging Access reduces parity-memory writes at the SIMD-register level. Erasure-Parity Mapping unifies data and parity recovery into one decoding path. Traversal Pattern Selection specializes the dominant single-erasure case. Encoding uses CFWP together with NMA. Decoding uses CFWP together with EPM and TPS. The next four slides walk through each technique with its corresponding figure from the paper.
}

\subsection{Cache-Friendly Window Partitioning}

\begin{frame}[t]{Key Idea 1 -- Cache-Friendly Window Partitioning}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.42\textwidth}
  \begin{itemize}
    \setlength{\itemsep}{0.45em}
    \item Tile each chunk into \textbf{cache-sized windows}.
    \item Finish all \sxor updates in one window before the next.
    \item \textbf{On-demand init} -- no full zero pass up front.
    \item Window size $W$: smallest power of two with $W \ge k{-}1$.
  \end{itemize}

  \vspace{0.4em}
  \begin{block}{Effect}
  \small Localized access $+$ one fewer full traversal.
  \end{block}

  \column{0.58\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.68\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Cache-Friendly_Window_Demonstration.pdf}

  \vspace{0.1em}
  {\scriptsize Colored segments: local access within one window.}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
\note{
The first key idea is Cache-Friendly Window Partitioning, or CFWP. Instead of scanning whole chunks end-to-end, we tile each chunk into small cache-sized windows and complete every shift-XOR update inside one window before moving to the next. One important implementation detail is on-demand initialization: we do not pre-zero the entire chunk, we simply initialize each window on its first use, which removes one full traversal of memory. For the window size, we pick the smallest power of two that is at least k minus one, which is exactly enough to cover all shift offsets introduced by the Two-tone matrix when substitution is advanced by one window ahead of elimination. Experimentally this minimal window size gave us the best throughput. The overall effect is localized access and one fewer full traversal, which benefits both encoding and decoding.
}

\subsection{Neighbor-Merging Access}

\begin{frame}[t]{Key Idea 2 -- Neighbor-Merging Access}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.42\textwidth}
  \begin{itemize}
    \setlength{\itemsep}{0.45em}
    \item XOR \textbf{two adjacent} data symbols in SIMD registers \textit{first}.
    \item Then write the merged result to parity \textbf{once}.
    \item Cost drops to $\Theta\!\bigl(k + \tfrac{km}{2}\bigr)l$.
    \item Keeps horizontal locality, halves parity writes.
  \end{itemize}

  \vspace{0.4em}
  \begin{block}{Why only pairs?}
  \small 256-bit AVX2 register budget + offset complexity.
  \end{block}

  \column{0.58\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.68\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Neighbor-Merging_Access_Pattern.pdf}

  \vspace{0.1em}
  {\scriptsize Adjacent data XOR-merged in registers \textbf{before} touching parity.}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
\note{
The second key idea is Neighbor-Merging Access, or NMA, which attacks the parity-write bottleneck that we saw on the limitations slide. In a horizontal pass, adjacent data-chunk symbols are loaded into SIMD registers and XORed together first, and only the merged result is written out to parity. The right brace in the figure highlights exactly this in-register merge before any parity update. The memory-access complexity drops from k plus k times m, down to k plus k times m over two, which is clearly better than horizontal and, in practical configurations, also better than vertical. We deliberately merge only pairs of symbols, because with AVX2 we have a fixed 256-bit register budget, and merging more chunks would also complicate the shift offsets. The net effect is that we keep horizontal-style read locality while halving parity-memory pressure.
}

\subsection{Erasure-Parity Mapping}

\begin{frame}[t]{Key Idea 3 -- Erasure-Parity Mapping}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.42\textwidth}
  \begin{itemize}
    \setlength{\itemsep}{0.45em}
    \item Unify erased \textbf{data} and erased \textbf{parity} under one abstraction \texttt{mpe}.
    \item Erased parity re-encoded \textbf{inside} elimination, not after it.
    \item Removes the standalone repair pass.
  \end{itemize}

  \vspace{0.4em}
  \begin{block}{Benefit}
  \small Fewer memory round-trips; one decoding path for all erasure patterns.
  \end{block}

  \column{0.58\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.68\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Erasure-Parity_Mapping_Decoding_Demonstration.pdf}

  \vspace{0.1em}
  {\scriptsize Dashed arrows $=$ traversals eliminated by fusion.}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
\note{
The third key idea is Erasure-Parity Mapping, or EPM, which tackles the decoding side. Traditionally the decoder first recovers lost data and then runs a separate parity repair phase. In FastTT we unify the two. Every erased chunk, whether data or parity, is represented by one shared abstraction we call "mpe", which records the erased chunk together with its matched survived parity. Survived data are substituted into these mpe entries, and during elimination, decoded symbols are immediately reused to update the entries that correspond to erased parity chunks. In the figure, the dashed arrows and the strike-throughs indicate exactly the traversals that this fusion removes. The concrete benefit is fewer memory round-trips and a single decoding path that handles every erasure pattern uniformly, instead of a separate repair stage at the end.
}

\subsection{Traversal Pattern Selection}

\begin{frame}[t]{Key Idea 4 -- Traversal Pattern Selection}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.42\textwidth}
  \begin{itemize}
    \setlength{\itemsep}{0.45em}
    \item Real clusters: \textbf{single-chunk loss dominates}.
    \item For that case $\Rightarrow$ skip full elimination.
    \item Use the \textbf{vertical} pattern: one-pass XOR of survivors.
    \item Fall back to EPM for multi-erasure cases.
  \end{itemize}

  \vspace{0.4em}
  \begin{block}{Result}
  \small Single-erasure decoding accelerated by \textbf{$>$130\%} vs. ISA-L.
  \end{block}

  \column{0.58\textwidth}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth,height=0.68\textheight,keepaspectratio]{Vertical_Traversal_Pattern_Demonstration.pdf}

  \vspace{0.1em}
  {\scriptsize One missing chunk reconstructed in a single XOR pass.}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
\note{
The fourth key idea is Traversal Pattern Selection, or TPS. This is based on a strong practical observation: in real storage clusters, the probability of losing exactly one chunk dominates the probability of losing two or more simultaneously. For that single-erasure case, full Two-tone elimination is unnecessary. FastTT reuses the vertical traversal pattern introduced earlier and reconstructs the missing chunk with a single XOR pass over the survived chunks, as shown in the figure. For any other case, we fall back to the unified EPM path instead of trying to optimize every pattern. This is a narrow but high-impact specialization: as we will see in the results, it gives more than 130 percent decoding speedup over ISA-L in the common single-erasure case, while the fallback path protects correctness and performance for multi-erasure recovery.
}

% =====================================================================
% Flagship results
% =====================================================================
\section{Flagship Results}
\subsection{Industrial and Academic Baselines}

\begin{frame}[t]{Flagship Results -- Throughput in Ceph}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.5\textwidth}
  \begin{block}{vs. Ceph production baselines}
  \scriptsize
  Intel i9-14900K $\cdot$ AVX2 $\cdot$ 2\,MB chunks
  \begin{itemize}
    \item vs. ISA-L: \textbf{$+59.1\%$} encode, \textbf{$+50.9\%$} decode
    \item vs. Jerasure: \textbf{$+261\%$} encode, \textbf{$+161\%$} decode
  \end{itemize}

  \vspace{0.2em}
  \resizebox{\linewidth}{!}{%
  \begin{tabular}{lrrrrrr}
    \toprule
    & \multicolumn{3}{c}{Encode (GB/s)} & \multicolumn{3}{c}{Avg. decode} \\
    \cmidrule(lr){2-4} \cmidrule(lr){5-7}
    $(k,m)$ & \textbf{FastTT} & ISA-L & Jera. & \textbf{FastTT} & ISA-L & Jera. \\
    \midrule
    $(6,2)$ & 34.7 & 24.4 & 17.0 & 60.8 & 31.6 & 29.5 \\
    $(6,3)$ & 31.7 & 17.6 &  7.6 & 46.2 & 27.5 & 20.7 \\
