  \end{tabular}}
  \end{block}
\end{columns}

\vspace{0.2em}
{\tiny Avg. decode $=$ averaged over erasure counts $1..m$, for both data- and parity-chunk losses.}
\end{frame}
\note{
Now the headline results. I want to present the industrial and academic comparisons with equal weight. On the left is the comparison against the Ceph-integrated production baselines, ISA-L and Jerasure. On the right is the comparison against Cerasure, the most recent academic state-of-the-art. In every decoding number shown here, "avg. decode" is the throughput averaged over all erasure counts from one up to m, covering both data-chunk and parity-chunk losses. Against the Ceph baselines, FastTT delivers plus 59.1 percent average encoding and plus 50.9 percent average decoding versus ISA-L, and much larger gains against Jerasure. Against the academic SOTA Cerasure, we still gain plus 13.2 percent encoding and plus 16.0 percent decoding on average, with a peak decoding gain of 43.6 percent. The single headline number to remember is that single-erasure decoding, which is the dominant failure case in practice, improves by up to 182 percent over ISA-L thanks to the TPS fast path.
}

\subsection{Ablation of the Four Techniques}

\begin{frame}[t]{Flagship Results -- Ablation on $(8,3)$}
\footnotesize
\begin{columns}[T,totalwidth=\textwidth]
  \column{0.55\textwidth}
  \centering
  \resizebox{\linewidth}{!}{%
  \begin{tabular}{ccccrr}
    \toprule
    CFWP & NMA & EPM & TPS & \textbf{Encode} & \textbf{Decode} \\
    \midrule
      &   &   &   & 13.2 &  7.5 \\
      &   & \checkmark &   & 13.2 & 16.9 \\
    \checkmark &   & \checkmark &   & 23.3 & 24.1 \\
    \checkmark & \checkmark & \checkmark &   & 31.2 & 24.1 \\
    \checkmark & \checkmark & \checkmark & \checkmark & \textbf{32.8} & \textbf{35.2} \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabular}}

  \vspace{0.3em}
  {\tiny Throughput in GB/s; decode averaged over erasure counts $1..m$.}

  \column{0.45\textwidth}
  \begin{itemize}
    \setlength{\itemsep}{0.45em}
    \item \textbf{EPM}: first jump in \emph{decode} \\ \small ($7.5 \to 16.9$, $+100\%$) -- fusion matters.
    \item \textbf{CFWP}: lifts both encode \& decode \\ \small ($+77\%$ enc, $+43\%$ dec).
    \item \textbf{NMA}: pure encoding gain \\ \small ($23.3 \to 31.2$, $+34\%$).
    \item \textbf{TPS}: second decode jump \\ \small ($24.1 \to 35.2$, $+46\%$).
  \end{itemize}

  \vspace{0.3em}
  {\footnotesize Each technique plays a distinct, non-redundant role.}
\end{columns}
\end{frame}
\note{
This slide explains why the gains happen, one technique at a time, on the representative (8,3) configuration. Start from the top: the naive baseline gives 13.2 encode and 7.5 decode. Turning on EPM alone doubles decoding to 16.9, which confirms that redundant traversal in the decoding flow was a real bottleneck. Then CFWP lifts encoding from 13.2 to 23.3 and also pushes decoding from 16.9 to 24.1, so it contributes on both sides. NMA on top of that takes encoding to 31.2, and as expected it does not affect decoding. Finally TPS raises average decoding from 24.1 to 35.2, because single-erasure recovery is now on the fast one-pass path. The overall message is that each of the four techniques plays a distinct and non-redundant role, and together they close the gap between Two-tone in theory and Two-tone in practice.
}

